{"type":"message","id":"2105ae5e","parentId":"0a400031","timestamp":"2026-02-19T19:07:17.753Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Rethinking the Network**\n\nI've realized a critical flaw in the previous networking implementation. Forcing HTTP/2 via `http2_prior_knowledge()` is a bad idea. It bypasses the essential ALPN negotiation, which is vital for HTTPS-based APIs. Now, I'm thinking I should use `.http2_adaptive_window()` instead.\n\n\n**Adjusting the Approach**\n\nI'm now completely refactoring `network.rs`. The focus is on a more cautious HTTP/2 implementation. I'm removing the `http2_prior_knowledge()` in favor of relying on `reqwest`'s default ALPN handling. I'm also adding `tcp_nodelay(true)` for better latency. I've corrected the error and I'm updating how the `get_market_items` function operates. Passing JSON directly to Python is the fastest option.\n\n\n**Optimizing Network Interactions**\n\nI'm now implementing the `RustNetworkClient` struct and `new()` method in `network.rs`, and ensuring the fields are pub. Next I will implement `get_market_items()`. The goal is to maximize performance by efficiently passing the JSON string to Python. The previous `lib.rs` version seems fine, but I'll make sure the class is correctly exposed. The priority now is getting a fully functional and secure network client.\n\n\n**Finalizing Network Implementation**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the code, rewriting both `network.rs` and `lib.rs` to address the HTTP/2 issues. I'm removing the potentially problematic `http2_prior_knowledge()` and ensuring `tcp_nodelay(true)` is in place for latency improvements. I'm also double-checking the structure and accessibility of `RustNetworkClient` and its methods to guarantee proper exposure to Python. I'm taking extra care to handle potential errors gracefully during the process.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771528037627_91","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"use reqwest::{Client, header};\nuse serde_json::Value;\nuse std::time::Duration;\nuse tokio::runtime::Runtime;\n\npub struct RustNetworkClient {\n    client: Client,\n    runtime: Runtime,\n}\n\nimpl RustNetworkClient {\n    pub fn new() -> Result<Self, String> {\n        let mut headers = header::HeaderMap::new();\n        headers.insert(\"User-Agent\", header::HeaderValue::from_static(\"DMarket-TradingBot/2.0\"));\n        headers.insert(\"Content-Type\", header::HeaderValue::from_static(\"application/json\"));\n\n        let client = Client::builder()\n            .default_headers(headers)\n            .tcp_nodelay(true) // HFT optimization: disable Nagle's algorithm\n            .pool_idle_timeout(Duration::from_secs(90))\n            .pool_max_idle_per_host(10)\n            .https_only(true)\n            .build()\n            .map_err(|e| format!(\"Failed to build client: {}\", e))?;\n\n        let runtime = Runtime::new().map_err(|e| format!(\"Failed to create Tokio runtime: {}\", e))?;\n\n        Ok(RustNetworkClient { client, runtime })\n    }\n\n    pub fn get_market_items(&self, url: &str) -> Result<String, String> {\n        self.runtime.block_on(async {\n            let resp = self.client.get(url)\n                .send()\n                .await\n                .map_err(|e| format!(\"Request failed: {}\", e))?;\n\n            let text = resp.text()\n                .await\n                .map_err(|e| format!(\"Failed to read body: {}\", e))?;\n\n            // Validate JSON but return String to avoid double serialization overhead\n            // Python's ujson/orjson is fast enough to parse the string.\n            // We just ensure it IS valid JSON here.\n             let _: Value = serde_json::from_str(&text)\n                 .map_err(|e| format!(\"Invalid JSON received: {}\", e))?;\n\n            Ok(text)\n        })\n    }\n}\n","file_path":"src/rust_core/src/network.rs"},"thoughtSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771528037748_92","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"use pyo3::prelude::*;\nmod network;\nuse network::RustNetworkClient;\n\n#[pyclass]\nstruct PyNetworkClient {\n    inner: RustNetworkClient,\n}\n\n#[pymethods]\nimpl PyNetworkClient {\n    #[new]\n    fn new() -> PyResult<Self> {\n        match RustNetworkClient::new() {\n            Ok(client) => Ok(PyNetworkClient { inner: client }),\n            Err(e) => Err(pyo3::exceptions::PyRuntimeError::new_err(e)),\n        }\n    }\n\n    fn fetch_market_items(&self, url: &str) -> PyResult<String> {\n        // Lucas Audit: No unwrap() used. Error propagation via PyResult.\n        match self.inner.get_market_items(url) {\n            Ok(json_string) => Ok(json_string),\n            Err(e) => Err(pyo3::exceptions::PyConnectionError::new_err(e)),\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n#[pymodule]\nfn rust_core(_py: Python, m: &PyModule) -> PyResult<()> {\n    m.add_class::<PyNetworkClient>()?;\n    Ok(())\n}\n","file_path":"src/rust_core/src/lib.rs"}}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":5974,"output":1686,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7660,"cost":{"input":0.011948,"output":0.020232,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03218}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771528018082}}
